 name containing a `$`, but that seems normal in this context. Is that okay? It feels like I'm on the right track!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering method visibility and risks**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about the potential risks involved. I need to use the `@static` annotation in Scala carefully, especially in cases where GetMethod looks for public methods. It's important to ensure that the `@static` methods I implement really are public static. I wonder if there are any caveats or additional considerations I should be aware of while implementing this to avoid issues down the road.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_h0L0iPWxRTEkth2qDrys7xYp|fc_02cb8d4e695670b70169f7d92e64f08194846586e7e7795b4a\", \"name\": \"write\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/com.typesafe.akka/akka-protobuf-v3_3/2.9.0-M2/src/test/scala/com_typesafe_akka/akka_protobuf_v3_3/UnsafeUtilTest.scala\", \"content\": \"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\npackage libcore.io {\\n  import scala.annotation.static\\n\\n  final class Memory private ()\\n\\n  object Memory {\\n    @static def peekLong(address: Long, swap: Boolean): Long = 0L\\n    @static def pokeLong(address: Long, value: Long, swap: Boolean): Unit = ()\\n    @static def pokeInt(address: Long, value: Int, swap: Boolean): Unit = ()\\n    @static def peekInt(address: Long, swap: Boolean): Int = 0\\n    @static def pokeByte(address: Long, value: Byte): Unit = ()\\n    @static def peekByte(address: Long): Byte = 0\\n    @static def pokeByteArray(address: Long, value: Array[Byte], offset: Int, length: Int): Unit = ()\\n    @static def peekByteArray(address: Long, value: Array[Byte], offset: Int, length: Int): Unit = ()\\n\\n    @static def peekLong(address: Int, swap: Boolean): Long = 0L\\n    @static def pokeLong(